CONTEXT
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
After Task 3, chat_controller.py is the boundary between:
  - The new Pydantic-style CurrentUser (no collection_agents field)
  - The old workflow state TypedDicts (still expect collection_agents)

The controller currently calls `user.get("collection_agents")` in
six places. With the new CurrentUser dict, all six return `{}` or
None, which silently breaks the workflows. The line 137 bug
(form submission permission check) is the worst — it always
returns "You don't have permission" because the lookup returns [].

This task removes the chat_controller's dependency on
`collection_agents` entirely, replacing it with user identity
fields (`emp_no`, `group_idx`, `role_ids`) that workflows in Tasks
4.2-4.4 will use for DB-driven permission checks.

ARCHITECTURAL DIRECTION:
  - Workflow initial_state will carry IDENTITY fields, not
    permission fields.
  - Each workflow's own permission_check_node will do its own DB
    lookup using those identity fields (added in Tasks 4.2-4.4).
  - chat_controller does not carry permission state across the
    boundary.

The form submission permission check (line 137) is moved or
removed. Decision: REMOVE it from chat_controller. Each workflow
that produces form widgets is responsible for checking submission
permissions when the form comes back. This keeps chat_controller
identity-only.

